<li style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">
<p><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">When a process wants to duplicate itself so that the parent and the child can each execute different sections of code at the same time. This is common for network servers—the parent waits for a service request from a client. When the request arrives, the parent calls </span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Courier;">fork </span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">and lets the child handle the request. The parent goes back to waiting for the next service request to arrive.</span></p>
</li>
<li style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">
<p><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">When a process wants to execute a different program. This is common for shells. In this case, the child does an </span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Courier;">exec </span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">(which we describe in Section 8.10) right after it returns from the </span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Courier;">fork</span><span style=" font-size: 10.000000pt; font-family: Palatino;">.</span></p>
</li>
</ol>
